[{"id":"VH950202","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><include href=\"../Passage/VH950189.qti.xml\" xmlns:xi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude\"></include></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Which of the following best explains why Steen produced paintings like the one in <span class=\"formatted_text text_decoration:underline\">image 1</span> for wealthy Dutch merchants?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VH950202_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<div class=\"stimulus_reference\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">\n<p class=\"standalone_statement style:1\"><span class=\"formatted_text text_decoration:underline\">Image 1</span></p>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<p class=\"title_line passage-title\">Jan Steen, Dutch painter, The <span class=\"formatted_text font_style:italic\">Burgher of Delft and his Daughter</span>, 1655</p>\n</div>\n<img alt=\"The figure presents a painting from the 1600s titled The Burgher of Delft and his Daughter. The painting shows a well-dressed man sitting on a bench on the stoop of a house. A well-dressed young girl walks down the steps of the house. Next to the stoop a woman and boy in peasant’s clothes are shown addressing the man. The woman’s hand is extended and the boy has taken his hat off.\" height=\"477\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH950189.g09.png\" width=\"400\" /><span class=\"mandatory_credit_line\">In the Public Domain</span></div>\n\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<p class=\"passage_para\"><span class=\"formatted_text font_style:italic\">The portrait most likely depicts the corn merchant Adolf Croeser and his daughter, Catharina. The burgher hears the plea of a begging widow and her son.</span></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p class=\"standalone_statement style:1\"><span class=\"formatted_text text_decoration:underline\">Image 2</span></p>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<p class=\"title_line passage-title\">Jan Steen, Dutch painter, <span class=\"formatted_text font_style:italic\">The Dissolute Household</span>, 1663-1664</p>\n</div>\n<img alt=\"The figure presents a painting from the 1600s titled The Dissolute Household. The painting shows a disheveled room with three people relaxing around a table. Children have gathered around one of the women who is asleep at the table, and the man at the table is smoking a pipe. In the background, a woman is shown dancing while a man plays the violin.\" height=\"402\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH950189.g10.png\" width=\"450\" /><span class=\"mandatory_credit_line\">Apsley House, The Wellington Museum, London,UK/Bridgeman Images</span></div>\n</div>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The merchants wished to show their Protestant rejection of Catholic imagery.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The merchants wished to show their support for the imposition of royal absolutism.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The merchants wished to show that their prosperity did not compromise their moral beliefs.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The merchants wished to show their knowledge of classical artistic styles and influences.</p>"],"answer":2}]